text: That's not how Tsunamis work...  1.) The occur when there is a seizmic event off shore... not inland as San Andreas is under San Fran. (Explostion, volcanic activity, subductions... these can all cause a Tsunami). Now perhaps the San Andreas is close enough to produce a small Tsunami, but I'm fairly certain that we'd know about the potential tsunami of a San Andreas quake by now... after all there have been a few. (Of course, none of those are ever likely to be as large as the quakes that hit Fukushima, Japan or Christchurch, NZ). I doubt they could create anything bigger than maybe a few feet of rise... if that.  2.) A Tsunami does not appear as a 'breaking wave,' instead all the water in the are tends to suck out and then return as rising tide. Thus the other term for Tsunami - 'Tidal Wave.' Yes, the tide that comes in quickly swamps everything, and moves very far inland... but it is not a massive breaker wave.  Did no one pay attention during the massive quake off the shore of Fukushima in Japan... you know the one from 2011? That was not even a full four years ago. The videos were all over the net.  Also... how is this not a Roland Emmerich movie?

text: So a magnitude 9 in a modern city that's aware (and therefore developed according to) of a nearby fault, causes all of this?¬†  The largest recorded in human history (which takes no claim for the record in Earth's history) was a 9.4 in Chile. Damage was nothing like this.  We had the 9.2 in 2004 that caused the boxing day tsunami and actually knocked the Earth slightly off of its axis. Again, the damage was nothing like this.  And living in New Zealand and having gone through many, many powerful earthquakes myself, I can tell you that earthquakes do not feel or look like that. I also live in Wellington, which actually sits ON TOP of its major fault line and only just over 100 years ago a massive earthquake on a fault line further up the island caused land to rise out of the harbour and reshaped the entire area - and that wasn't even on the fault line or as powerful as what is being predicted for the future of Wellington. Predictions of how it will be also do not match ANYWHERE near the over-the-top level of destruction seen in this trailer.   This is some 2012 nonsense here.

text: San Andreas is a slip strike fault. It will not cause ground waves, and the shaking is in the wrong direction! It's east to west! San	Andreas is too far inland to cause tsunamis! The buildings will sink, not fall over! Ground liquefies! Okay, done ranting. We of the west coast have a more dangerous fault to think about, which San Andreas is an off shoot of. It is called the Cascadia subduction zone. What happened in Japan and in the Indian ocean is getting ready to happen here. It has already happened 13 times already, the last one on January 26, 1700, at around 9 pm. To see actual proof of Cascadia's power, go see the underwater forest on the tip of the peninsula of Washington state. 330 years ago, that forest was entirely above water. During the 1/26/1700 earthquake, the ground was yanked down nearly 30 feet. In some areas, most noticeable in Mukilteo, Washington, the ground was shoved up 30 feet. Cascadia tends to rupture anywhere between 300 to 980 years. A rupture on the San Andreas can and has triggered a rupture on Cascadia. Midwest, you guys aren't safe ether. You have the Madrid fault system, where a rupture in the early 1800s caused the Mississippi river to flow backwards for a few hours and created an island in the river. East Coast, you guys are not quake free ether. You have a fault system responsible for the Charleston earthquake. I know quakes. I have been studying them for a novel I'm planning.

text: The most frighting thing is that it can happen, or actually, it WILL happen, but who knows when. And yes, earth will literally crack open (then fill with water): look at the Sea of Cortez in the Baja Peninsula in Mexico. That peninsula used to be part of the continental mainland, now it's a peninsula. The San Andreas fault will turn part of California and Baja California (Mexico) into an island: everything south of San Francisco and west of the Central Valley. The fault goes right through El Cajon Pass (I-15) in San Bernandino, then right between Mount St. Gorgonio and Mt. St. Jacinto (I-10). Then under Salton Sea and ends in the delta of the Colorado River in Mexico. The fault is so big it can be seen from space, just open Google Earth and you will see something that looks like a big scar in the middle of California, follow it and you will see what I'm talking about.¬† Ever wonder why the mountain range seems to turn west north of LA instead of following ¬†a straight line from the San Diego mountains to the Sierra Nevada? That's the San Andreas fault bending the range, it literally moves mountains...

text: In order to generate a tsunami (as depicted in the trailer) the earthquake would need to occur at a convergent boundary with subduction zones. The San Andreas fault is a right-transform fault. There is no vertical change of the Pacific plate, thus an earthquake along the San Andreas fault would not cause a tsunami.  Tectonic plates have a relative direction of motion. Therefore there are convergent, divergent, and transform plate boundaries. Convergent boundaries create zones of subduction which can generate the vertical disturbance needed to generate a tsunami.¬†  Warner Bros. Pictures needs to learn a little more science before they make people actually think that the San Andreas fault might cause a tsunami in LA....there are plenty of other fault lines which have subduction zones that can cause a tsunami to hit LA... but not the San Andreas.

This isn't an end of the world movie, for the whole of humans will not be wiped out, so don't go off dismissing it as a shitty movie because of that. Call it a shitty movie because of another reason. text: The 'Big One' is a hypothetical earthquake of magnitude ~8 or greater that is expected to happen along the SAF. Such a quake will produce devastation to human civilization within about 50-100 miles of the SAF quake zone, especially in urban areas like Palm Springs, Los Angeles and San Francisco. No one knows when the Big One ("BO") will happen because scientists cannot yet predict earthquakes with any precision. The 1906 San Francisco quake (mag ~7.8) and the 1857 Ft. Tejon quake (mag ~7.9) took place in northern and central California, respectively, and both were 'Big Ones'. Some scientists think the next BO will be in southern California. The SAF passes through LA's three main transportation, power, and utility corridors in southern California: I-10 in San Gorgonio (Banning) Pass, I-15 in Cajon Pass and I-5 in Tejon Pass. The San Francisco peninsula's water supply is contained in San Andreas Lake (!) and the Crystal Springs reservoirs, both squarely on the SAF. Earthquakes with magnitude 8.5 or greater can probably only happen in California north of Cape Mendocino where the Cascadia megathrust subduction zone lies, but they are extremely rare, occurring on average once every few hundred years.

text: Very disappointed with this movie.¬† It's odd how we have all the technology to make special affects now unlike older movies, but then it gets ruined and misused because of unrealistic storylines and bad scripting.¬† The whole idea for this movie could literally have been epic, its long over due that a massive earthquake will occur somewhere on the west coast but not like how this movie portrays it.¬† Probably the main thing that ruined this movie was the tsunami scene which was just ridiculous and not realistic in any way.¬† Sometimes less is more, and everyone on earth knows how tsunami's work they don't just come as a huge 500 meter tall wave of water, its fast but more gradual in appearance.¬† It would never have been that high and it looks like they just made it like that so they could include a scene where the bridge gets destroyed, very lame.¬†¬† Another thing that totally ruined the movie was the horrible storyline, like the step dad who left his daughter.¬† For what was taking place in the movie they could have had more nostalgic moments instead of acting like this was every day life for them.¬† Oh and one last thing when the mother is rescued off the top of that building she has blood all over her side of her head, but then after they crash the helicopter and are in the truck she has no blood and looks like she just went to the spa.

text: I've watched it on our TV last night and thank the Lords Of Kobol for the commercial breaks, which gave me a few priceless moments to wipe away the tears of mirth and blow my nose.  Every disaster movie clich√© you ever saw or heard of, every contrived perilous moment and every clich√©d line of badly-written script was here. It never let up for a moment and the whole movie was so awful it was enormously entertaining.  I knew we were in trouble in the opening scenes with the dopey girl driving a winding mountain road and, in the face of oncoming traffic, reaching, and looking, into the back seat for her water bottle. Then, having survived that moment of utter idiocy, she gets her cell phone out and starts reading texts, still on the winding mountain road and in the face of oncoming traffic.  From there, things just got worse. San Andreas lived down to everything I expected of it and, so far as I was concerned, the highlight of the wretched thing was any shot of Alexandra Daddario's cleavage.
